[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Hollingsworth is an 89-year-old female who was well-known to Dr Sullins from previous surgery.  Dr. Sullins performed a right hemicolectomy for colon cancer and then repeat colectomy for recurrence in the transverse colon.  She has done well for the last several years but recently developed diarrhea and had a colonoscopy to assess for the cause of the diarrhea.  She was found to have a plaque-like lesion in her sigmoid colon which was biopsied and shown to be adenocarcinoma.  CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis did not suggest any metastatic disease, and she has a normal chest x-ray.
Dr Sullins asked Mrs. Hollingsworth how her bowel function was.  She claims that her bowel function is overall good, though she does have episodes of incontinence and urgency.

[end section id="20103"]

